# What is Gitlab
-> GitLab is a web-based DevOps platform that provides tools for the entire software development lifecycle â€” from planning and coding to testing, deployment, and monitoring. 
-> Itâ€™s similar to GitHub or Bitbucket but with a broader focus on end-to-end DevOps rather than just source code management.

Hereâ€™s what GitLab offers:
-> Version Control: Built on Git, so you can manage and track your source code, branches, and commits.
-> CI/CD Pipelines: Automates building, testing, and deploying code using GitLab CI/CD.
-> Project Management: Issue tracking, Kanban boards, milestones, and roadmaps for agile workflows.
-> Collaboration: Merge requests (like pull requests in GitHub), code reviews, and inline comments.
-> Security & Compliance: Built-in code scanning, vulnerability management, and auditing tools.
-> Container & Cloud Support: Integrated Docker registry and Kubernetes support for deployments.
-> Self-hosted or SaaS: You can use GitLabâ€™s cloud service (gitlab.com) or install GitLab on your own servers for full control.

ðŸ‘‰ In short: GitLab = Git (source code control) + CI/CD + DevOps + Collaboration in one platform.


# What is the difference between git, gitlab and github
ðŸ”¹ Git
What it is: A distributed version control system (DVCS).
Purpose: Lets developers track changes in source code, collaborate, branch, and merge.
Scope: A tool installed locally (command-line or GUI).
Types:
GitHub-hosted runners â†’ managed by GitHub, automatically scale, preloaded with common tools.
Self-hosted runners â†’ you install an agent on your own VM/server.

ðŸ”¹ GitLab
What it is: A web-based DevOps platform built on top of Git.
Purpose: Provides Git repository hosting plus CI/CD pipelines, project management, issue tracking, container registry, etc.
Scope: A platform to manage and automate the software development lifecycle.
Types:
Shared runners â†’ provided by GitLab (cloud).
Specific/self-hosted runners â†’ you install GitLab Runner on your server, VM, or Kubernetes.

ðŸ”¹ GitHub
What it is: Another web-based Git repository hosting service (like GitLab).
Purpose: Provides repo hosting, collaboration features, actions (CI/CD), project boards, code reviews, etc.
Scope: Also a platform, mainly focused on collaboration and open-source communities.

âš–ï¸ Key Practical Difference
GitLab: Native CI/CD, everything controlled via .gitlab-ci.yml. Pipelines are tightly coupled with GitLab UI.
GitHub: Relies on GitHub Actions (YAML-based workflows). Very flexible and extensible with community actions.


# What is the difference between Github actions and Gitlab
ðŸ”¹ GitHub Actions
-> Style â†’ Event-driven (triggers like push, PR, release).
-> Feels Like â†’ Chaining steps inside workflows.
-> Strength â†’ Huge Marketplace of ready-made actions, very quick to integrate.
-> Best For â†’ GitHub repos, open-source, fast automation.

ðŸ”¹ GitLab CI/CD
-> Style â†’ Structured pipeline with stages (build â†’ test â†’ deploy).
-> Feels Like â†’ Defining an assembly line for DevOps.
-> Strength â†’ Built-in DevOps tools (container registry, monitoring, approvals, security scans).
-> Best For â†’ Teams using GitLab end-to-end for source code + DevOps lifecycle.

ðŸ”¹ Jenkins
-> Style â†’ Server-based, jobs are defined with Jenkinsfile (Groovy syntax).
-> Feels Like â†’ Building pipelines with plugins (very customizable but more manual setup).
-> Strength â†’ Highly flexible via 1,800+ plugins, can integrate with almost any tool.
-> Best For â†’ Enterprises needing self-hosted, custom automation across many systems (not just Git).


# Which is â€œbetterâ€?

Choose GitHub Actions if:
Your code is already on GitHub.
You want quick setup with minimal maintenance.
You prefer reusable actions from the marketplace.

Choose GitLab CI/CD if:
You use GitLab for repos + project management.
You want all-in-one DevOps (code â†’ CI/CD â†’ monitoring â†’ registry).
You want flexibility with runners (Docker, Kubernetes).

Choose Jenkins if:
You need maximum flexibility and integration with non-GitHub/GitLab systems.
Youâ€™re in an enterprise with complex legacy pipelines.
You donâ€™t mind managing servers, plugins, and agents yourself.

# Simple answer:
Modern teams â†’ GitHub Actions or GitLab CI/CD (less maintenance, faster setup).
Large enterprises/legacy systems â†’ Jenkins (ultimate flexibility, but more work).

# What is Gitlab Runner
-> Gitlab runner is an application that pick up and execute the CI/CD jobs for gitlab
-> Gitlab runner is a open source
-> We have two types of runner 
    Shared runners â†’ provided by GitLab (cloud).
    Specific/self-hosted runners â†’ you install GitLab Runner on your server, VM, or Kubernetes.
